1. What is a String?

A String is a sequence (collection) of characters.

A character can be:

Letters (A-Z, a-z)
Numbers (0-9)
Symbols (@, #, $, %)
Spaces

In Python, strings are written inside single quotes (' ') or double quotes (" ").

Example
name = "Vivek"

or

name = 'Vivek'

Here,

V i v e k

These five characters together form one string.

2. Why Do We Need Strings?

Imagine creating applications like:

WhatsApp
Instagram
Gmail
Facebook
Google Search
ChatGPT

All of these process text, and text is stored as strings.

Without strings, we cannot:

Store names
Store passwords
Send messages
Search words
Validate email addresses
3. Real-Life Example

Think about your own details.

Name : Vivek Taware

The computer stores this as:

name = "Vivek Taware"

Another example:

Email:
vivek@gmail.com

Stored as:

email = "vivek@gmail.com"

Even your phone number can be stored as a string if you don't perform calculations on it:

phone = "9876543210"
4. Characteristics of Strings
1. Ordered

Characters have fixed positions.

Example:

word = "Python"
Character	Position (Index)
P	0
y	1
t	2
h	3
o	4
n	5

Every character has its own index.

2. Immutable

A string cannot be changed after it is created.

Example:

name = "Python"

Trying to change one character:

name[0] = "J"

This gives an error because strings are immutable.

Instead, create a new string:

name = "Jython"
3. Iterable

We can access every character one by one.

Example:

for ch in "Python":
    print(ch)

Output:

P
y
t
h
o
n
5. String Indexing

Each character has an index.

String

P  y  t  h  o  n
0  1  2  3  4  5

Python also supports negative indexing.

P   y   t   h   o   n
-6 -5 -4 -3 -2 -1

Example:

word = "Python"

print(word[0])
print(word[3])
print(word[-1])

Output:

P
h
n
6. String Length

To find the number of characters:

word = "Python"

print(len(word))

Output:

6
7. Common String Operations
Concatenation (Joining)
first = "Hello"
second = "World"

print(first + " " + second)

Output:

Hello World
Repetition
print("Hi " * 3)

Output:

Hi Hi Hi
Membership
text = "Python"

print("P" in text)
print("z" in text)

Output:

True
False
8. Solved Example Program
Problem

Write a Python program to:

Store your name.
Print the name.
Print the first character.
Print the last character.
Print the length of the string.
Program
name = "Vivek"

print("Name:", name)
print("First Character:", name[0])
print("Last Character:", name[-1])
print("Length:", len(name))
Output
Name: Vivek
First Character: V
Last Character: k
Length: 5
9. Time & Space Complexity

For the operations we learned today:

Operation	Time Complexity
Access character	O(1)
Find length (len)	O(1)
Traverse string	O(n)
Concatenate two strings	O(n + m)
10. Interview Tips
Strings in Python are immutable.
Indexing starts from 0.
Negative indexing starts from -1.
A string is also an iterable, so it works with loops.
Most interview problems involve traversing strings efficiently.
